{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"99c3e4cd-d6e8-4fd7-b265-d4606c6ab372","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead. This is more precise — it asserts exactly *which call* should throw:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    // Optionally assert on the exception details:\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n}\n```\n\n**Why?** `[ExpectedException]` catches exceptions from *any* line in the test (including the arrange step), masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes it to the exact call and lets you inspect the exception.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6d303424-2df3-467a-b11b-3563d978887e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question - no need to explore a codebase.","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"0BE0:3B272C:3C66CF:463D8A:69F00CCE"},"id":"975a69bd-86e5-467d-92ff-d48e272b296c","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:26:44.293Z","parentId":"d9e36010-e318-413b-8a9e-076ee1a20a8b"}
